
" '''a consultancy which analyses corporate reputations and watches online trends closely''', has used its '''blog-sniffing software''' to find out what was available on the internet before Diebold bought GES. It discovered that not only were a couple of voting-rights activists calling attention to the machines' drawbacks on their blogs well before the acquisition, but also that research papers highlighting the problems were available on technical websites. Diebold did traditional forms of due diligence before buying GES, such as verifying its financial health. But by ignoring the blogosphere, it failed to spot some crucial risks."
(citation from the Economist, source: http://www.smartmobs.com/archive/2006/02/15/corporations_t.html)

